<br>
VI has in place a pseudo-fair system to determine what is right and what is wrong.  However, we as players, use and even manipulate these rules to our advantage in order to advance or make gain for our characters.  We find that there are written rules and unwritten rules.  For instance, it is written that whoever deals the killing blow on a mob ultimately has the loot rights to that mob.  Yet, it is unwritten that if someone is camping a mob and has the forces available to kill it, that the chance be offered to them without interference.  It is written that a combination of names which spells a phrase (Such as Curemy Booboos) is not allowed.  It is unwritten that you do not narq on someone who has an unlawful name combination.  <br>
<br>
We then find that it is even more important to maintain respect for each other and to abide by unwritten rules when friendships or allies are involved.  Trust can only be formed when situations like these are resolved immediately and do not escalate.  So how does one determine whether they are right or wrong….whether they are deserving or undeserving?  The unwritten rules account for the things that GM’s can not create rules for....the unwritten laws imply respect for other players.<br>
<br>
Ultimately, I will not argue what is write or wrong.  To do so would be completely futile.  The answers to the problems that are currently being voiced are not as simple as we wish they could be.  What I do know and what I can say is this...<br>
<br>
